  <activity xml:id="quadratic-inequality-coeff-greater-than">
    <introduction>
      <p>Recall that when solving a quadratic equation, you can first try to factor the quadratic. Solving inequalities will require multiple steps. Solve the quadratic inequality <me>x^2-4x \gt 32</me>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
      <p> How can we graphically solve the inequality above? What are the values on the <m> x-axis</m> where the shading begins and ends? Shade on the x-axis where the inequality is a true statement.
        <ol marker="A." cols="1">
          <li><p><m>-8,4,</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>-4,8</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>4,8</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>-8,-4</m></p></li>
      </ol> </p>
    </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
      <p> How do these values from part <m>(a)</m> relate to the quadratic function, <me>f(x)=x^2-4x-32</me>?
        </p>
    </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
      <p> How can we find the <m>x-intercepts</m> algebraically for the quadratic function, <me>f(x)=x^2-4x-32</me>?
       </p>
    </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
      <p> When we graph the quadratic function, <me>f(x)=x^2-4x-32</me>, where is the function above the <m>x-axis</m>? 
        
    <ol marker="A." cols="1">
        <li><p> <m>x \gt 8</m>, <m>x \lt -4</m></p></li>
        <li><p><m>x \gt -8</m>, <m>x \gt -4</m></p></li>
        <li><p> <m>x \lt 8</m>, <m>x \lt 4</m> </p></li>
        <li><p> <m>x \lt -8</m>, <m>x \gt 4</m> </p></li>
        
    </ol> </p>
  </statement>
  </task>
  <task>
    <statement>
    <p> Now use interval notation to write your answers from part <m>(d)</m>.
    <ol marker="A." cols="1">
      <li><p><m>(-8,4)</m></p></li>
      <li><p> <m>( 4,8)</m></p></li>
      <li><p> <m>(-\infty,-4)\cup(8,\infty)</m></p></li>
      <li><p> <m>(-\infty,-8)\cup(4,\infty)</m> </p></li>
      
  </ol> </p>
</statement>
</task>
  <task>
    <statement>
    <p> How can we check if these intervals are correct or not?
       </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
  <statement>
  <p> How can we check algebraically if the quadratic function in part <m>(b)</m> is positive or negative?
     </p>
</statement>
</task>
  </activity>
  <remark> A sign chart is a number line representing the <m>x-axis</m> that can be used to show where a function is positive or negative.</remark>
  <activity xml:id="quadratic-inequality-coeff-less-than-0">
    <introduction>
      <p>Solve the quadratic inequality algebraically<me>5x^2+63 \lt 52x</me>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>Write the solution using interval notation.</p>
        <ol marker="A." cols="1">
          <li><p><m>\left(-9,-\frac{7}{5}\right)</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>\left(-\infty,\frac{7}{5}\right)\cup\left(9,\infty\right)</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>\left(-\frac{7}{5},9\right)</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>\left(\frac{7}{5},9\right)</m></p></li>
      </ol> 
    </statement>
    </task>
  </activity>
  <activity xml:id="quadratic-inequality-coeff-greater-than-or-equal-0">
    <introduction>
      <p>Solve the inequality <me>-2x^2-10x-10 \ge 6x+20</me>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
      <p> Write the solution using interval notation.
        <ol marker="A." cols="1">
          <li><p><m>[-5,-3]</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>(-\infty,-5]\cup[-3,\infty)</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>[3,5]</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>(-\infty,3]\cup[5,\infty)</m></p></li>
      </ol> </p>
    </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
      <p> How can we confirm visually that our solution is correct?
         </p>
    </statement>
    </task>
  </activity>
  <activity xml:id="rational-inequality-greater-than-0">
    <introduction>
      <p>Solve the rational inequality <me>\frac{5x-3}{x+4} \gt 7</me>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
      <p> How can we use technology to solve the inequality above? What are the values on the <m> x-axis</m> where the shading begins and ends? Shade on the x-axis where the inequality is a true statement.
        <ol marker="A." cols="1">
          <li><p><m>-\frac{31}{2},-4</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>\frac{31}{2},-4</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>\frac{31}{12},-4</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>-\frac{31}{12},-4</m> </p></li>
      </ol> </p>
    </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
      <p> Combine the following and simplify to one rational expression <me>\frac{5x-3}{x+4} - 7</me>. 
        <ol marker="A." cols="1">
          <li><p><m>\frac{12x+31}{x+4}</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>\frac{12x-31}{x+4}</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>\frac{-2x+31}{x+4}</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>\frac{-2x-31}{x+4}</m></p></li>
      </ol> </p>
    </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
      <p> How do these values from part <m>(a)</m> relate to the numerator and the denominator of the combined rational function in part <m>(b)</m>? 
        </p>
    </statement>
    </task>   
<task>
      <statement>
      <p> How can we test the solution we found in part <m>(a)</m> and the <m>x-axis</m>? </p>
  </statement>
  </task>
<task>
    <statement>
    <p> For what values is the original inequality a true statement?  
  <ol marker="A." cols="1">
    <li><p> <m>x \gt -\frac{31}{2}</m>,<m>x \lt -4</m></p></li>
    <li><p><m>x \gt \frac{31}{2}</m>,<m>x \lt -4</m></p></li>
    <li><p> <m>x \gt -\frac{31}{2}</m>,<m>x \lt 4</m> </p></li>
    <li><p> <m>x \lt \frac{31}{2}</m>,<m>x \gt 4</m> </p></li>
</ol> </p>
</statement>
</task>
<task>
    <statement>
    <p> How can we express the answers to part <m>(e)</m> for the rational inequality using interval notation?
    <ol marker="A." cols="1">
      <li><p><m>\left(-\frac{31}{2},4\right)</m></p></li>
      <li><p> <m>(4,8)</m></p></li>
      <li><p> <m>(-\infty,-4)\cup(8,\infty)</m></p></li>
      <li><p> <m>(-\infty,-8)\cup(4,\infty)</m> </p></li>    
  </ol> </p>
</statement>
</task>
   
  </activity>
  <remark>The values on the <m>x-axis</m> where a function is equal to zero or undefined are called partition values.</remark>

  <activity xml:id="rational-inequality-both-sides">
    <introduction>
      <p>Solve the rational inequality <me>\frac{8x+16}{x-2} \le \frac{x+10}{x+5}</me>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
      <statement>
      <p> Write the solution using interval notation. 
        <ol marker="A." cols="1">
          <li><p><m>(-\infty, -5)\cup(2,\infty)</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>\left(-5,-\frac{6}{7}\right]\cup\left[-\frac{6}{7},2\right)</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>\left[-\frac{6}{7},2\right)</m> </p></li>
          <li><p> <m>\left(-5,-\frac{6}{7}\right]</m></p></li>
      </ol> </p>
    </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
      <p> 
        Compare the interval notation from Activity 1.7.5 to the interval notation for this activity. When do we include the partition values in the answer with a bracket?
         </p>
    </statement>
    </task>
  </activity>
  
